{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_jordan_ver01/data/sn91068401/00332892770/1937121601/0550.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE SIX\nPensions Os\n$1,450 Less\nThan Before\nFourteen Beneficiar\nies of State\u2019s Semi-\nAnnual Generosity\nto Widows\nState of Nor.th Carolina pension pay\nments to widows of Civil War vete\nrans were being distributed to benefi\nciaries today by Clerk of Superior\nCourt E. O. Falkner in the sum of sl,-\n450, which is considerably less than at\nanv time in recent years. The de\ncrease came about by removal of bene\nficiaries from the pension rolls, most\nly by deaths.\nSeven widows in Class A received\n$l5O each, or $1,050. In Class B weie\nsix widows, each of whom received\nSSO, cr S3OO. There was a check for\nSIOO for Grant Lewis, colored body\nservant of David Cooper. Lewis has\nlately died.\nState pension checks are paid twice\nyear, on December 15 and June 10.\nClass A pensions went to the fol\nlowing:\nBettie Falkner, widow of A. B.\nFalkner.\nPattie M. Harris, widow A. C. Har\nris.\nSarah R. Hicks, widow S. M. Hicks.\nNannie Landis, widow James R.\nLandis.\nMargaret Shaw, widow William D.\nShaw.\nAnn P. Tucker, widow of William T.\nTucker.\nLucy C.. Woodlief widow of Benj. T.\nWoodlief.\nClass B pension checks were paid\nto these widows:\nMary Ann Ayscue, widow O. L. Ays-\nCUq.\nRosa Brown, widow of James W.\nDuke.\nNora Finch Green, widow William\nA. Green.\nMargaret Grissom, widow of James\nVANCE\n\u201cHenderson\u2019s Family Theatre\u201d\nLAST DAY\n\u201cMR. BOGGS STEPS OUT\u201d\nSTARTS FRIDAY\nDo your part. Some useful article\nof food or clothing is your price of\nadmission, Thursday, Dec. 23rd.\nElectrical Suggestions Suggestions Real Hlgh Gra^ e\nAppliance Oifts Metal Smokers 1 00 3-piece Uviig Room Suites as low Fumiture GlftS\nTable Lamps, $2.50 up \u20acoffee Tables, $5.00 Tubes*\"*\u2122*\u00ae Royal Easy Chairs $39.50 up\nChildren\u2019s Desks with Chairs $7.50 WgjSjWJjSJ Ol a I Carpet Sweepers Solid Mahogany Governor Winthrop\nD litre Lane Cedar Chests, $22.50 up Dvnam' Cabine t Secretaries\nIvllgS I Uynamic Speaker f Sellars Kitchen Cabinets\nConsole Tables, $3.50 Cabinet Models Police Calls m _ D\u2019 nnflS in Qnlid Ma-\nAll standard size rugs in newest __ I Domestic Bra mi I Breakfast Room Suites Dining Room Pieces 1\npatterns Occasional Tables, $4.50 to $35.00 at $49.95 Superh\u00abf\u00bb dcas \u00bbs V hogany, Chippendale, and\nl uperb *terodynt I Dinette Suites can-Phyfe. and Colonial designs\nSize 9 x 12 $14.95 up Windsor Rockers and Chairs, Porcelain Top Tables\nFelt Base Rugs, size 9 x 12, large s7 t 0 s2s o BffV^flWiH il Children\u2019s High Chairs, $3.50 Solid Mahogany Bedroom Suites,\nassortment of patterns, $6.50 Occasional Chairs and Rockers, $6.00 A Wew t-lectnc Tuning Set $89.95 Solid Walnut Lamp Tables, $7.50 Sheraton and Colonial design*\nHENDERSON FURNITURE CO.\nH. Grissom.\nJosephine T. W. M. Tunstall. widow\nJ. B. Tunstall.\nMRS. ROOKER WILL\nBE BURIED FRIDAY\nFuneral services for Mrs. Mary\nWhite Rooker, who died in Rich\nmond. Va., will be conducted here to\nmorrow. according to information re\nceived here.\nThe body will arrive in Henderson\ntomorrow morning at 8:20 o\u2019clock,\nand be carried to Barnes Funeral\nHome. At 2 o'clock Friday afternoon,\nservices will be conducted at Carey\u2019s\nChapel, and interment will be made\n\u2022\u201ehere.\nSupport Develops\nIn Congress For\nLiberal Spending\n(Continued from Page One.)\niteen urged to sign a public statement\nadvocating a ter.-point program to\nstop the business recession.\nThe steps suggested were revision\nof business taxes, approach toward a\nbalanced budget: \u201cjust relations be\ntween capital and labor,\u201d a reliance\non profitable investment of private\nsavings, recognition of the profit mo\ntive, and superiority of the competi\ntive system, assurance of the safetv\nof collateral, reduction in the general\ntax burden, maintenance of states\u2019\nrights, economic and non-political dis\ntribution of relief, and preservation\nof the American system of private en\nterprise.\nNo one would claim authorship of\nthe document. Some legislators re\nported it had been prepared by a\nsmall group, including Senator Bailey,\nDemocrat, North Carolina.\n\u201cThere was a general feeling in the\nSenate,\u2019\u2019 Bailey said, \u201cthat there ought\nto be an understanding fcetween each\nother on what should be done about\nthe business recession. Nobody, how\never, has been authorized or detailed\nto frame a platform.\u201d\nGrahamites Are\nPleased by Hoey\nfContinued from f*age One.)\npictured the $6,600 job in possession\nof another who picked the guberna\ntorial winner even before the first pri\nmary last year.\nAs a matter of fact there ar P many\nindications that Governor Hoey had\nevery intention to appoint somebody\nelse until almost the eleventh hour.\nThere is more than a mere modicum\nof evidence to support the idea that\nhe even went so far as to offer the\npost to Charlotte\u2019s City Manager\nMarshall, but Mr. Marshall, having\nrecently received a boost in pay to\nSIO,OOO per year notch, quite natural\nly declined to sacrifice the difference.\nBut whether or not the governor\nwas driven to his choice, it is eminent\nly satisfying to the Grahamites. Along\nwith practically everyone else they\nregard Senator Stacy as peculiarly\nqualified for the post. They were for\nhim first because they believe him\nthe best man available and only sec\nondarily because hs belonged to the\nHENDERSON (N. C.) DAILY DISPATCH, THURSDAY, DECEMBER 16, 1937\nDR. SHOT PASSES\nAT LYNCHBURG, VA.\nFormer Presbyterian Pastor\nHere; Funeral Friday,\nIn Charleston\nDr. Alexander Sprunt, former pas\ntor of the First Presbyterian church\nin Henderson, and later for many\nyears pastor of the Scotch Presbyte\nrian church in Charleston, S. C., died\nat 1:50 o\u2019clock yesterday afternoon in\nMemorial hospital, (Lynchburg, Va.,\naccording to a telegram received by\nMrs. I. B. Gary late Wednesday.\nDr. Sprunt was on a visit to his\nson, Rev. James Spnint, in Lynch\nburg, when he fell and broke his lip.\nComplications developed, and he ling\nered for four weeks before his death.\nFuneral sei\u2019vices will he held Friday\nin Charleston, where Dr. Sprunt was\npastor emeritus of the Scotch Pres\nbyterian church to the time of his\ndeath.\nDr. Sprunt is remembered here by\nmany friends of former years, as well\nas many now residing in Henderson.\nHe was pastor here from 1884 to 1891.\nHe went from here to a church in\nRock Hill. S. C., where he remained\nuntil 1899, when he was called to the\nCharleston church. He served there\nuntil 1936, when he wished to retire\nfrom active service. The Charleston\nchurch declined to accept his resigna\ntion and elected him pastor emeritus.\nHis successor was named only six\nmonths ago.\nIn 1921 he was elected moderator of\nthe General Assembly of the Southern\nPresbyterian Church, an honor that\ncomes to but few.\nDr. Sprunt was in Henderson early\nin November, when his son, Alexand\ner Sprunt, Jr. .also of Charleston, and\nsouthern director of bird sanctuaries\nfor the American Audubon Society,\nlectured to the Henderson Bird Club,\nand a large audience of Henderson cit\nizens and outside visitors. He went\nfrom here to Lynchburg to visit his\nson, pastor of a Presbyterian church\nthere.\nDr. Sprunt\u2019s wife died about a year\nand a half ago. He is survived by the\nfollowing sons and daughters: Dr.\nTom Sprunt, Baltimore, Md.; Alexan\nder Sprunt, Jr., Charleston, S. C.;\nRev. James Sprunt, Lynchburg, Va.;\nI\u00abtrs. James S. White, Rock Hill, S. C.;\nand Mrs. Lacy L. Little, a missionary\nin China.\nA New York columnist believes that\nthe wearing of a lapel flower (bou\ntonniere to you, you aristocrat!) is a\nsure sign of success. Wow, what com\nplete failures George Washington and\nAcraham Lincoln must have been!\nGraham faction.\nInasmuch as Senator Stacy was him\nself a candidate during the first pri\nmary days of 1936 his support of\nSandy Graham \"was more or less \u201con\nthe quiet\u201d, and perhaps that\u2019s why\nGovernor Hoey did not let it debar the\nRockingham man from recognition.\nCotton Plan In Farm\nBill Is Defeated\n(Continued from Page One.)\napparently was the bill at which Wal\nlace\u2019s remarks were directed.\nSenator Bailey read from a news\npaper statement about the Lee sub\nstitute plan attributed to Wallace,\nand saying its licensing of business\nwould be \"a step toward fascism or\nautocracy and so forth.\u201d\n\u201cI thank the secretary of agrcul\nture for his warning,\u201d Bailey said.\n\u201cSome time ago there was a protest\nagainst the radicalism of the secretary\nof agriculture. Now, Mr. Wallace is\nthe one who is publicly warning us.\u2019\nState Contesting\nTuckertown Order\n(Continued from Page Opo.)\nlina\u2019s objections to the decisions, as\nset forth in its petition for the re\nhearing follow:\n\u201c1. The commission erred in find\ning that th e interests of interstate or\nforeign commerce would he affected\nby the Tuckertown project.\n(a) The undisputed testimony show\ned that the Yadkin-Peedee river is\nnot navigable in the vicinity of the\nproposed Tuckertown plant and any\nfinding by the commission that the\nTuckertown project is to be located\non navigable waters of the United\nStates is arbitrary, in direct contra\ndiction of the testimony and unsup\nported by any evidencq whatsoever.\n(b) The undisputed testimony show\ned that the Tuckertown project could\nnot. under any system of operation,\nhave any measurable effect upon the\nnavigablet capacity of the navigable\nsection of the Yadkin-P\u2019eedee river,\nand the finding of the commission\nthat the interests of interstate or for\neign commerce would be affected by\nthe Tuckertown project is, therefore,\narbitrary, in direct contradiction of\nthe testimony and unsupported by any\nevidence whatsoever.\n(c) The undisputed testimony show\n/foAtt MJMSKUU.\nor ill\nV ,W T 0\nZC \"TL ~TV&\nfrZ Rj Z oc\nDEAR. NOAH= DOES A\nHOT DOG HOWL TO\nCATSUP\nEAB.U CE.UME iEuKHAB-T/ IND\nDEAR. A\nCHICKEN PEEPS/ DOES\nHE ALWAYS SEE WHAT\nHE IS LOOKING FOR.?\nDOROTHYCREECH HICKOR-V, N. C.\nDEAR. NOAH=IF A CHASM\nYAWNS AND THE FENCE\nGAPS, WILL THE WIND\nSING TO THE DROWSY\nWATERS MR.S. u. F.\ned that the present dams and hydro\nelectric plants upon the river would\neliminate any possible theoretical ef\nfect that the Tuckertown project\ncould have upon the stage of the water\nat any point in the course of the\nriver. The finding of the commission\nwas. therefore, arbitrary, in direct\ncontradiction of the testimony, and\nunsupported by any evidence what\nsoever.\n(d) The undisputed testimony show\ned that in recent years the use of the\nYadkin-Peedee river for commercial\npurposes was negligible. There was no\ntestimony that such commerce, neg\nligible in amount, was interstate or\nforeign, or of any but a purely local\nnature. The finding of the commis\nsion. is. therefore, speculative, con\njectural and unsubstantiated by any\nevidence.\n\u201c2. The Tuckertown project is plan\nned to be constructed on the Yadkin\nriver, which has been held by the\nhighest court of thf* State of North\nCarolina to be non-navigable (State\nv Tyre Glen, 52 N. C. 248; Cornelius\nv Tyre Glen. 50 N. C. 394). The con-\nNOTICE OF COMMISSIONER\u2019S\nSALE.\nUnder and by virtue of an order of\nthe Superior Court of Vance County,\nN. C., made in the special proceed\ning, entitled Bessie R. Finch and hus\nband, S. W. Finch, E. C. Reavis and\nwife, Rose R. Reavis, Gladys R.\nMabry and husband, C. J. Mabry, A.\nW. Reavis and wife, Nannie F. Reavis,\nP. F. Reavis and wife, Mae S. Reavis,\nRuth R. Shaw and husband, J. T.\nShaw, M. W. Reavis, (single), J, A.\nReavis and wife, Curlie G. Reavis,\nheirs of W. Harvey Reavis, deceased,\nex parte, the same being No. 4042 up\non the special proceeding docket of\nsaid court, the undersigned commis\nsioner will, on Monday, the 10th day\nof January, 1938, at 12 o\u2019clock, at the\ncourthouse door in Henderson, N. C.,\noffer for sale to the highest bidder\nfor cash, the following described\nproperty:\nBounded on the North by the lands\nof the heirs of John Smith, (now\nHenderson and Warrenton old road),\non the East by the lands of Stephen\nMabry\u2019s heirs, (now E. G. Finch\u2019s\nheirs), on the South by the lands of\nM. Buchanan, Inow Norman N.\nHarris), on the West by the lands of\nD. 11. Reavis\u2019 heirs, it being that tract\nof 147 1-4 acres, (less 60 acres, and\nless 1-4 acre), of land bought by R.\nP. Reavis, W. H. Reavis and Charity\nKearney from James A. Crews and\nwife, Martha A. Crews by deed dated\nDecember the 13th, 1877, which deed\nis duly registered in Warren County,\nN. C., in Book 42, Page 337, to which\ndeed reference is hereby made. Also\ndeed Book 8, Page 274, in Vance Coun\nty Register of Deed\u2019s office.\nThere is excepted from the above\ndescribed tract of land, a 60 acre tract\nof land sold to C. B. Reavis, March\n16th, 1914. See deed recorded in Reg\nister of Deed\u2019s office, Vance County,\nN. C., Book 65, Page 153. There is also\n1-4 of an acre excepted and reserved\nas a curial ground and is now used\nas such, with suitable ingress and\negress. Excluding the above excep\ntions, this tract of land contains 87\nacres, more or less.\nThis the 9th day of December, 1937.\nE. C. REAVIS,\nCommissioner.\nR. B. Carter, Attorney.\ntrol of non-navigav.e streams with\nin a State is expressly reserved by the\nConstitution of th e United States to\nthe State, and the State of North Car\nolina, therefore, has exclusive juris\ndiction over the Yadkin river. The ac\ntion of the Federal Power Commis\nsion in assuming jurisdiction over\nthe Tuckertown project constitutes an\ninvasion of the sovereign and prop\nrietary rights of the State of North\nCarolina in violation of the Constitu\ntion of the United States, particularly\nthe Tenth Amendment thereto.\n\u201c3. The requirements of Section 23\nof the Federal Power Act are not ap\nplicable to head-water developments\nof non-navigahle streams, but applv\nonly to locations where the stream is\nnavigable in fact and in law. The com\nmission was, therefore, without juris\ndiction to pass upon any questions in\nvolving the control of the Yadkin-\nPeedee river in the non-navigable\nsection in *he vicinity of the Tucker\ntown project.\nThe State\u2019s petition is signed by At-\nBOOM! BANG! BOOM!\nFIREWORKS\nFor Christmas\ni\nThe Largest Variety We Have\nEver Shown.\nCome in Today and\nMake Your\nSelections\nStocks Are Now Complete\nDon\u2019t wait until the last minute. Buy\nyours now. Nothing the children enjoy\nmore than fireworks.\nH. B. NEWMAN\u2019S\nFireworks Store\nAcross Street From Motor Sales Co.\nSame Location Used Last Year.\ntorney General A. A. F\nAssist ant Attorneys General i 311(1\nMcMullan and Wade Bruton. H Ulv\nPeople who take interest in +u-\ning start off in quest of trut* hink\ncall themselves philosophers nr\ndents of philosophy. stu\n18. H. MIXON\n;;J (Incorporated)\n;j Contractor and\nj Builder\n\u201cBuilds Bette* BuibUvqs\u201d\n1 Als o Wall Papering, Pai n ti n\nJ Hoofing and Termite\nH Extermination.\nPhone 7","height":"28239","width":"21195"}}
